review_blob: Pours nearly as dark as a porter with a deep red hue and a medium tan to off-white head. Smells of raisin, plum, and malt. High carbonation gives it a crisp and refreshing finish despite its weight and sweetness. Used a snifter to enhance aroma/appearance. Solid brew...potent.

Impressive stout that has obviously stayed true to its European roots. All the thick and creamy goodness you expect from a stout with a Dark Chocolate bitterness in the finish. If you enjoy stouts, youll certainly enjoy this one.

Not my favorite Four Peaks brew, but worth a try none the less...especially for beer enthusiasts. The balance is exceptional, which is the key to any solid ESB. Toasted malt with a slight resin aftertaste. Poured slighty darker than expected.
Cloudy yellow with a medium white head and a very pronounced clove and banana afterstase and aroma. Not a Hef fan, but this brew is as good as any Ive tried.

Not for beer enthusiasts per se, but a good introduction to real beer. Started the GF off on the sunbru and worked her way into Kiltlifter. A light bodied summertime brew with a faint toasted banana aftertaste. Not my favotire but a necessary brew for any pub.

Not the measure of perfection that the Hop Knot is, but Raj has been a Four Peaks Staple for years now. Any IPA lover should give this a try. Dark amber with a medium white head. Pine and Caramel notes with an IPAs resin aftertase.

Double Hop is officially my new favoite brew by Four Peaks. Served in a smaller snifter due to the high alcohol content, this beer is bright bronze in color with a medium white head. Taste and aroma of sweet pine, with a more delicate malt finish than you would expect from a double IPA. Hop Knot is a great beer and this is doubly great!
Dense Irish ale for beer lovers only. Malt is predominent with just enough hops to lighten the load. Caramel, coffee, and nuts with a faint citrus finish.

Tried this beer on the go. It was a great summertime beer on a hot New York day. Defintely a surprise coming from this very ordinary container. You can taste the quality of the hops and the finish is crisp citrus. Where can I buy a sixer??

An admittedly deliecious thought, this brew seems to have crossed into stout territory. I wasnt able to detect the hop that would separate this beer from stout and porter. Strong coffee and light vanilla aftertaste. Bad batch? Will try again...

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Tried this beer in a little Irish Pub just outside of Time Square. I have to say, this discovery was one of the hilights of my trip. If this is a fruit beer, its well concealed inside a pale ale. Brilliant aroma with a delicate assorted fruit aftertaste. Must have more!

On tap as a seasonal at TGI Fridays in Glendale AZ. By far the best beer available at this location. Full of flavor...obvious citrus and hops with a well balanced aftertaste. Abrassive to the tongue yet smooth to the palate. A good brew by Sam
Not as much kick as a Stone or even Sierra Nevada but overall I enjoyed this beer. While the hops arent quite as precise as other pale ales it is definitely a very clean, great tasting brew.

This is actually my beer of choice. Cloudy pale orange, with a nice foamy head. Toss the orange aside, as I am not a fruit in beer kinda guy. Tastes citrusy and crisp with a hint of spice in the aftertaste. A good change of pace from your every day heff.

Alright, Ive been waiting for this one... Pours a deep brown, almost black with a madium to large off-white head. Smells of merlot and malt. Definite dark berry/plum/raisin undertones with a very subtle spicy hop finish. Not as thick as I would have guessed. The aftertaste is a faint plum spice. Worth the wait Id say. Great brew.

Limited winter 04 release, 10.06% alc...evidently they vary. This is the second barleywine Ive tried and they seem to keep getting better. Caramel, citrus, and malt maybe roasted malt flavor with a surprising dry hop finish. Medium white head with a caramel hop aroma. Id love to try it on tap some day, maybe my next trip to San Diego. Anywho, great beer...Its really starting to kick in now so Ill enjoy whats left of it.

Ive noticed that people basically just bash any lager they come across...I dont know if its fighting the mass produced lager craze or something else, but I am sure that compared to most lagers Ive tried this one isnt bad at all. Certainly more taste than the big three...a little fruity with a dry, clean finish. Not fantastic, but its a decent lager and worth a try...cheap at world market.

Honestly one of the better IPAs Ive tasted, and Ive tasted the highest ranked IPAs on this site. Not as acidic as a typical IPA but not lacking in flavor. Just writing this makes me wish I had one in hand right now. The balance seems to be perfect with no aftertaste...at least no aftertaste that youd mind hanging on to for a while. Goes great with the Burmeister Burger.

Light amber color with a creamy white head. Strong  citrus and hop aroma...almost pine. Sweet at first sip then the bitter kicks in as it rolls back. Refreshing aftertaste with a nice warm feeling on the way down. Def. worth a try if youre in the mood for some hop.
Small foamy white head that dissappears rather quickly. Faint roasted malt flavor and aroma with more pronounced hops than a typical lager. Not bad overall.

Served in a funky glass and omitting a seemingly funky aroma...certainly not what Im used to at least. Not to devaluate this brew as I did enjoy it, there was a faint wet, sanitized aroma rising from the glass. As for the taste its big, sweet, and obviously fairly potent...topped off with a large frothy white head. Def. worth a try and another great brew by Four Peaks.

Sometimes Im not sure whether the beer was good or if I was just craving a good beer. This one I thought was a decent brew (for a pale lager). Certainly better than the big three American versions. Goes well with Asian cuisine, as you would expect, and seemingly hits the spot. Id have it again under the right circumstances.
Nice amber ale...a little more hop than others Ive tried. Medium frothy head smells more like a mild american pale ale. Clean, crisp aftertaste...not a bad brew at all.
Little or no head...similar aroma. Neither the hop nor strength of an IPA. Seemingly a little watered down, although the actual taste is not bad. A good try but probably not something Id have again.

Good brew here, more hoppy in my opinion than people seem to give it credit for. I thought it was a perfect balance of hops and malt. The taste was wonderful although the depiction on the bottle leaves a harsh first impression. My first maibock and definitely worth a try.

Pours dark, not at all transparent, with a meduim darker than offwhite head. Smells of raosted oats, chocolate and earth. Crisp when it first hits the tongue, then the malt and roasted flavor kicks in. The aftertaste is slightly more acidic than other porters Ive tried. Very tasty overall and def. worth trying if you like porters, sierra nevada brews, or just a good beer.
Good brew overall. Tried on tap an Macayos. Thick head, citrus flavor, impressive hop taste. Not great, but a good American Pale Ale. Worth trying.

I know most people are fairly impressed with this brew but it didnt really do much for me...I may have to give it another try. As for the beer I had, there was literally no head, just a few stray bubbles. I cant really define any specific taste due to the fact that it was so watered down tasting. Perhaps just a bad batch or pour...either way it deserves a low score on this occasion.

This, unfortunately, is the first beer Ive tried from Rio Salado. It almost reminds me of the "High Life", which is not a compliment. Actually Id probably rather have a high life than a thunderbolt based on the sour aftertaste. Just not enjoyable overall.
beer_name: Rio Salado Lightning Bolt Pilsner Blond Lager

review_blob: This may seem like an ambitious rating, but this was honestly everything I expect from a portter. Smelled great! like roasted oatmeal. Went down super smooth with a dry hoppy finish. Similar to stone smoked porter only a bit thicker. If youre a local porter fan, you should give this one a try.
This is a great American Pale Ale. I cant drive by a Rock Bottom here in AZ without thinking about this beer. Citrus aroma, smooth/hoppy taste with no aftertaste. Solid brew here...a must.
beer_name: Rock Bottom Ahwatukee Desert Trail Pale Ale

review_blob: Poors light, smells light, tastes light. Can I follow that up by saying that its not a bad beer. It gets the job done. If you have to go Mexican...go Pacifico.

So I went on a trip to Mexico recently. I find it funny that Mexican citizens talk about this beer like its roughly the equivalent of Americas "Beast". Only thing worse than this, as Mexican beers go, is Sol.

I had no idea what to expect with this one. I wasnt even sure what I had once I poured it. One thing Ill say for this brew...I gave it the full scale for appearence. So frothy, it looked like a cream soda float. Smooth as all hell with no commanding taste. Good for a try and maybe an occasion. I actually threw some on the steak I was cooking...turned out pretty damn tasty.

This is a fruit beer? by the taste I thought it was a pale lager. Not terrible...might even hit the spot on a warm day, but not to be consumed for the pleasure of it. Not a bad price, however, and certainly better than the "big three".

This beer was not as impressive as I had hoped. After trying the anchor porter, I couldnt wait to see what else they had to offer. What I got was a bitter beer, which I was expecting, and an acidic unpleasant aftertaste, which was a complete suprise. Ill give this one another shot down the road...but for now...

This is a brew that you dont have to search high and low to find, as most bars will stock it. Light aroma, but you can smell the hops. Amber in color with a respectable head. Not a great, but definitely a good all aorund beer that I could see myself stocking on occasion.

This is a perfect example of an american pale ale in my opinion. Better than Sierra Nevada with a particular taste that I can recognize as Stone. Some wrote that this was an overly malty brew but to me the hops are clearly there, in the aroma and taste. This is the kind of beer I can drink on any occasion....like right now.

Pours cloudy dark orange with a frothy white head. ..5 min later and the bubbles are still rising. Citrus aroma and the taste to match. The pine taste must account for the resiny aftertaste which is strong at times although this beer pulls it off well. The warmth on the way down would signal the extra dose of alchohol. A very good IPA overall, although not quite as good as Stone.
The ole "Silver Bullet". Yada yada yada. Youve tried one mass produced light beer, youve tried them all. Dont waste your time here.

Whew! this stuff is sweet. So my girlfriend and I were at a bar when she ordered what seemed like a half gallon sized mug of this stuff. When she didnt like it guess who had to finish it off. I think I could drink a small glass of this to hit the spot. It is an interesting cider...just be sure your eyes arent bigger than your stomach.
Im not allowed to say that this stuff sucks because Id be stepping on the toes of a few people around here...but this stuff sucks. Just cant get into it. Ill take an Original coors over one of these.
Interesting brew, but it didnt quite measure up to my expectations. Very dry feel in the mouth with an overload of spice. I ws generous on my rating, but this will be my one and only try.
beer_name: Buffalo Bills Americas Original Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Pours very dark, but not quite as dark as Anchor or Stone porters with a roasted toffee aroma. Crisp on the tongue and in the mouth, with a lingering caramel, cafe aftertaste. This is my first try and Id say its a toss up between Fullers and Anchor for my top porter of choice. Ill def. have to see what else fullers has to offer. Great Brew.

My opinion is a slightly skewed, because after trying this brew, Id say that Im not a big fan of oatmeal stouts. It was a good looking beer with a faint toffee aroma. The flavor however was just not what Im used to...actually it tasted a little flat so maybe it was a bad sample. Just not enjoyable overall for me, but I can appreciate the complexity.

Great Brew! Fairly thick creamy head, slight tofee aroma and taste. The hops give it the perfect balance, neutralizing the caramel aftertaste. I would never believe anything this creamy would have a crisp finish. It def. convinced me to try more anchor brews...good stuff.
It is what it is...A smooth pale lager with no funky aftertaste. Not worth all the hype, but not a bad brew. I think its coming dow in price a bit also...if so Ill keep a couple on hand.

Pours black with an off-white head, almost identical to the picture. Wonderful crisp taste despite being such a dark beer. I can definitely taste hints of chocolate and cafe flavors. Slight burnt taste that complements the subtle overtones. Smooth brew...def. a good job by stone. At only 2.99 for 1.6 pints at trader joes, its a beer worth trying.

Golden in color with lots of carbonation. Decent bright white faomy head. Light beer taste thats better than your typical mass produced lager. Goes down smooth with no nasty aftertaste and hits the spot when you out for sushi or some other Japanese cuisine. Decent Beer.

Complex brew...definite burnt malt/caramel flavor with a hoppy/citrus finish. Kind of a war of the taste buds, between the malt and hops. Unfortunately my only chance to try this beer was at a temperature slightly colder than 70 degrees or so. Im going to re-rate this one once I get a nice cold sample.
